doc.after: Arthur Wilson was the 52-year-old Hull-based owner of a shipping business.[20] He built his home at Tranby Croft, in the East Riding of Yorkshire, as a Victorian country house, and he and his family moved in during the summer of 1876.[21] As well as a wife, Mary, he also had a son, (Arthur) Stanley Wilson, and a daughter, Ethel; her husband, Edward Lycett Green was the son of the local manufacturer and MP, Sir Edward Green.[22] Tomes reports that Gordon-Cumming may have previously propositioned Ethel Lycett Green.[3]
